---
title: "stdlib-design-philosophy"
author: bad-antics
date: 2026-04-05
abstract: The Lateralus standard library is designed to be small, opinionated, and free from ecosystem lock-in. In this essay, we'll explore what's in core vs optional modules, the tradeoffs behind these design choices, and why they benefit our users.

# Core Modules

Our core libraries are designed to be minimalistic yet comprehensive. We aim to provide a solid foundation for building robust applications without introducing unnecessary complexity.

// math module example
fn add(a: int, b: int) -> int {
    return a + b
}

// io module example
fn read_int(input: str) -> int {
    let digits = input.chars().map(|c| c.to_digit(10).unwrap());
    digits.sum()
}

## Optional Modules

We've also designed a modular architecture that allows us to add optional libraries as needed. This approach provides flexibility for developers while ensuring that our core libraries remain stable and maintainable.

// networking module example (optional)
use std::net::{TcpListener, TcpStream};

fn listen_for_connections() -> Option<TcpStream> {
    let listener = TcpListener::bind("localhost:8080")?;
    for stream in listener.incoming() {
        match stream {
            Ok(stream) => Some(stream),
            Err(_) => None,
        }
    }
}

## No Ecosystem Lock-In

One of our key design principles is to avoid ecosystem lock-in. By keeping our core libraries small and focused on the essentials, we ensure that users can easily integrate our code into their existing projects without worrying about proprietary dependencies.

This approach also makes it easier for us to collaborate with other developers and contribute to open-source initiatives. We believe that by working together, we can build better software for everyone.

## Tradeoffs

Of course, our design choices come with tradeoffs. For instance, our small core library means that some features might not be available out-of-the-box. However, this limitation also encourages users to focus on the essential functionality and build upon what's provided.

